  "text": "The two key source files in the Rust compiler responsible for (1) collecting candidate trait method implementations and (2) reporting ambiguous trait method errors are:\n\n1. **`compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/method/probe.rs`** — This file contains `ProbeContext`, the central structure for method resolution. It collects candidate trait method implementations via functions like `assemble_extension_candidates_for_trait` (which assembles candidates for a specific trait by checking if the trait defines a method with a suitable name), `assemble_candidates_for_bounds` (which assembles candidates from trait bounds), and `collapse_candidates_to_trait_pick` (which resolves ambiguity when multiple impls exist but all come from the same trait). The `ProbeContext` maintains two lists: `inherent_candidates` and `extension_candidates`. An ICE during this phase would manifest if unexpected state is encountered while iterating over or filtering candidates.\n\n2. **`compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/method/suggest.rs`** — This file handles error reporting for method resolution failures. Specifically, the `MethodError::Ambiguity` branch (around line 221) reports the \"multiple applicable items in scope\" error (E0034) when multiple trait methods match. It calls `note_candidates_on_method_error` to annotate the diagnostic with information about each candidate. An ICE could occur if the ambiguity data is malformed or if `note_candidates_on_method_error` encounters an unexpected candidate type.\n\n3. **`compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/method/mod.rs`** — Defines the `MethodError` enum (including the `Ambiguity` variant) and orchestrates method lookup, delegating to `probe.rs` for candidate collection and `suggest.rs` for error reporting."
}

